ADDING BEANS INTO SPRING CONTEXT\
\
@Bean notation\
- allows full control of the creation of the instance\
- can add more instances of the same type\
- can add any object instance type, the type does not need to be defined in your code/app\
- a separate method for each bean that needs to be created, so needs some boiler plate code\
\
\
@Component StereoType annotation\
- you only have control of the instance after the framework creates it\
- you can add only one instance of the class/type into the Spring context\
- only for classes that are in your own code/app\
- no need for boiler plate code\
\
\
Programatically\
\
\
\
\
RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN BEANS\
\
Wiring 		\
- relationship is implemented by directly calling a @Bean annotated method from another method annotated with @Bean that defines the second bean of the relationship\
\
\
Autowiring 	\
- Spring provides a value for a parameter you define for the @Bean annotated method\
 - inject the value in the field of the class which needs the dependency\
 - inject the value through the constructor of the class which needs the dependency, [not needed when only when constructor is present]\
\
\
\
HOW DOES SPRING CHOOSE A BEAN\
\
- a bean gets named by its creating method name OR with name attribute on @Bean notation.   [a beanID is the same as a bean name]\
- @Primary makes the bean a default choice\
- @Qualifier(<name>) can be used to name a bean via @Component and then @Qualifier(<name>) can be used to call a named bean\
\
\
\
BEAN SCOPES AND LIFECYCLES\
\
Singleton\
 - you get the same instance when you refer to a specific bean [even though multiple instance of the same type exist]\
 - for Spring singleton means unique per bean name (not unique per app)\
 - best for immutable beans\
 - this scope is not thread safe\
 - eager instantiation - spring creates the bean when it initializes the context\
 - lazy instantiation - spring creates the bean when the bean is first referenced\
\
Prototype\
 - spring does not create and manage the instance directly, rather it manages just the type\
 - a new instance is created when referenced\
 - since it is a new instance each time the instance is thread safe and mutable\
 - this is best used in my opinion when writing processing logic\
 - a name is associated with a type\
 - the instance is only created when it is referred\
